https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/ArrayList.html#sort-java.util.Comparator-  
Thank you, I am a novice and was puzzled by this behavior.  
 I found the answer.

when the sort method calls the compare method, it passes the arguments in the opposite order, with param2 first and param1 second.
This ordering may seem counterintuitive, but it is deliberate and consistent with the convention used in the Java API. The reason for this convention is to allow for greater flexibility in defining comparators. By swapping the order of the arguments, the compare method can be used to define a comparison in which the first argument is considered greater than the second or vice versa, depending on the needs of the application.

