Here is my recommendation. First a couple conventions.
- class names start with an uppercase letter
- fields and methods start with lower case and are usually in `camelCase`.
- make fields private and use getters/setters to preserve/enforce encapsulation

Also, a class usually has fields and items that pertain to that class. A `record` could also be used here if the class is immutable. 

Knowledge of other students does not make sense for a `Student` class.  A more obvious example might be a `Book` class which has info about a particular book, not all books.  However, a `Library` or `Shelf` class would certainly be appropriate for books depending on the use case.

For students, you could have a `Class` class which might have the name of the class and a list of students attending that class.
```
class Class {
    private String className;
    private List&lt;Student&gt; attendees = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();

    public Class(String name) {
        this.className = name;
    }
    public void addStudent(Student student) {
        System.out.println(&quot;Adding: &quot; + student);
        attendees.add(student);
    }
    
    public void displayAttendees() {
        attendees.forEach(System.out::println);
    }
    
    public String getClassName() {
        return className;
    }
}
```

I also recommend `Lists` over `arrays` since they can grow dynamically thus eliminating the need to track indices or resize the array.

