answers.body_markdown:
## To create X509Certificate from PEM string you need:

1) First you need to remove certificate headers from that PEM string.

   Headers are : `----BEGIN CERTIFICATE-----` and `-----END CERTIFICATE------`

2) Decode the rest of the part using `Base64` to byte array. It is safer to use `Base64.getMimeDecoder()` than `Base64.getDecoder()`, otherwise you may run into issue `java.lang.IllegalArgumentException: Illegal base64 character a`

3) Use `CertificateFactory` to convert byte stream to `X509Certificate` 


So, the code would look like this:

&lt;!-- language: java --&gt;
    public static X509Certificate buildX509Certificate(String certPem) throws CertificateException {
        X509Certificate x509Certificate = null;

        if (Objects.nonNull(certPem)) {
            CertificateFactory certificateFactory = CertificateFactory.getInstance(&quot;X.509&quot;);

            certPem = certPem.replace(&quot;-----BEGIN CERTIFICATE-----\n&quot;, &quot;&quot;)
                    .replace(&quot;-----END CERTIFICATE-----&quot;, &quot;&quot;);

            byte[] certBytes = Base64.getMimeDecoder().decode(certPem); // get cert bytes
            ByteArrayInputStream certInputStream = new ByteArrayInputStream(certBytes);
            x509Certificate = (X509Certificate)
                    certificateFactory.generateCertificate(certInputStream); // generate certificate
        }
        return x509Certificate;
    }

------

## To create SSLContext you need:

1) Create `KeyStore` 
2) Put your certificate into it 
3) Create `KeyManagerFactory` and init it from your keystore
4) Build `SSLContext` using `SslContextBuilder.forClient()`

So, the code would look like this:

&lt;!-- language: java --&gt;
    public static SslContext buildSSLContext(X509Certificate certificate, String alias) throws CertificateException, NoSuchAlgorithmException,
            KeyStoreException, IOException, UnrecoverableKeyException {
        KeyStore keyStore = KeyStore.getInstance(KeyStore.getDefaultType());
        keyStore.load(null, null); // Use a null input stream + password to create an empty key store.

        keyStore.setCertificateEntry(alias, certificate); // add certificate to keystore

        KeyManagerFactory keyManagerFactory = KeyManagerFactory.getInstance(KeyManagerFactory.getDefaultAlgorithm());
        keyManagerFactory.init(keyStore, null);

        // Create an SSL context that uses that certificate
        return SslContextBuilder.forClient()
                .keyManager(keyManagerFactory)
                .build();
    }

**Note**: `SSLContext` is from package `io.netty.handler.ssl`, not from `javax.net.ssl`

--------

## To configure your WebClient with SSLContext you need:

1) Create `ReactorClientHttpConnector` with `HttpClient.create().secure()` where you can pass your `SSLContext`
2) Build WebClient passing your `ReactorClientHttpConnector` to `.clientConnector()` method

So, the code would look like this:

&lt;!-- language: java --&gt;
    X509Certificate x509Certificate = buildX509Certificate(certPem);
    SslContext sslContext = buildSSLContext(x509Certificate, &quot;my_cert&quot;);
    
    ReactorClientHttpConnector reactorClientHttpConnector = new ReactorClientHttpConnector(HttpClient.create()
            .secure(sslContextSpec -&gt; sslContextSpec.sslContext(sslContext))
    );
    WebClient webClient = WebClient.builder()
            .clientConnector(reactorClientHttpConnector)
            .build();

-------
## UPDATED:

Probably in your case as your application is a client, you want just to verify identity of server. Then you should build `SSLContext` with `TrustManager`. Then your method `buildSSLContext()` would look like this:

    public static SslContext buildSSLContext(X509Certificate certificate) throws IOException {
        // Create an SSL context that trusts that certificate
        return SslContextBuilder.forClient()
                .trustManager(certificate)
                .build();
    }

